1. Basics¶

The R environment¶

In this workshop we are going to work with R studio which is an integrated development environment (IDE) for R. By clicking on the R studio icon in your desktop, a window like the one below should pop up.

Menu items: Several options for the user are available in this menu bar, including save and load projects and scripts (File tab), change font size and background color (Tools>Global Option), and set work directory (Session).

Workspace: Shows you the objects (e.g., tables, dataframes, arrays, function, etc) saved in your working directory. If you click on the History tab, you can access all your recent commands to the program.

R console: This is the place where the program is waiting for you to tell it what to do. You can type commands directly in this window and type enter to confirm. However, the commands are lost when you close the session. In order to avoid this problem, you can save all your commands on a script file (see section 4), which works similarly to a note pad. The symbol “>” means that the R console is ready to receive your next command. On the other hand, the symbol “+” indicates that the command typed is not complete. The keyboard key “Escape” (esc) cancel an incomplete command.

Files, Plots, Packages, Help, Viewer: On this window you can choose among 5 different options. The tab file shows you all files that were saved in the current directory. The tab file allows you to see plots that are created by the user via commands in the R console. The tab packages bring a list of all packages installed in your computer and shows you which of them are currently loaded. On the tab Help, the user can search for support regarding the use of specific functions, packages and even analysis. Finally, the tab viewer is a new option that is used to view local web content.

You can create a new project in R clicking on the File tab and then selecting New project> New Directory> Empty project> Create project. To check the working directory where all your saved files are being stored, use the function:

In [210]:

Scripts¶

Instead of typing all commands on the R console every time you open R, it is practical to use a script, which is a simple text document that is readable in R. To open a new script, select File>New File>R script. To save the script, select File>Save, or just click on the save button (looks like a floppy disk).

To run a code from the script window, you have to press CTRL + Enter together. The commands are run line by line. To run multiple lines at the same time, you have to select all the lines that you want and then press CTRL + Enter.

Return to the Summary

Important details¶

  • R is case sensitive (A ≠ a).
  • Do not use spaces in names of objects.
  • Do not start object names with numbers or special symbols (e.g., @, /, #).
  • Do not forget to close parentheses, quotation marks and brackets that are open.

Return to the Summary

Definition of some important symbols¶

Objects are assigned using the symbol “<-“ or the symbol “=”. I suggest you to always use the symbol “<-“. To call the object, just write the object name and press CTRL + Enter. For example:

In [79]:
object_name <- 1+2
object_name
3

The hashtag symbol (#) tells R that all things wrote after this symbol are a text and not a command. This is very useful because allow us to write notes in the middle of the code. For example:

In [80]:
1+2 # The result of this equation is three
3

Use single or double quotes to tell R to interpret something as a string. See below.

In [81]:
first_animal <- "fish"
second_animal <- 'cat'

Commas (,) separate arguments in a function.

In [82]:
rep (10, 5) # Repeat the number 10 (first argument) five times (second argument)
  1. 10
  2. 10
  3. 10
  4. 10
  5. 10

Relational operators: “>” means greater than; “<” means lower than; “==” means equal to; “<=” means equal or lower than; “>=” means equal or larger than; “!=” means different from. For example:

In [83]:
a <- 1
b <- 10
In [84]:
a > b
FALSE
In [85]:
a == b
FALSE
In [86]:
a != b
TRUE

Question mark (?) is used to access the documentation (help) of functions, symbols and packages. You can also use two question marks together (??) to search for specific subjects in the R Help System. This is useful when we don’t know the specific name of the function. We are going to talk more about this on section 8. See an example below.

In [88]:
?sum
sum {base}R Documentation

Sum of Vector Elements

Description

sum returns the sum of all the values present in its arguments.

Usage

sum(..., na.rm = FALSE)

Arguments

...

numeric or complex or logical vectors.

na.rm

logical. Should missing values (including NaN) be removed?

Details

This is a generic function: methods can be defined for it directly or via the Summary group generic. For this to work properly, the arguments ... should be unnamed, and dispatch is on the first argument.

If na.rm is FALSE an NA or NaN value in any of the arguments will cause a value of NA or NaN to be returned, otherwise NA and NaN values are ignored.

Logical true values are regarded as one, false values as zero. For historical reasons, NULL is accepted and treated as if it were integer(0).

Loss of accuracy can occur when summing values of different signs: this can even occur for sufficiently long integer inputs if the partial sums would cause integer overflow. Where possible extended-precision accumulators are used, typically well supported with C99 and newer, but possibly platform-dependent.

Value

The sum. If all of the M ... arguments are of type integer or logical, then the sum is integer when possible and is double otherwise. Integer overflow should no longer happen since R version 3.5.0. For other argument types it is a length-one numeric (double) or complex vector.

NB: the sum of an empty set is zero, by definition.

S4 methods

This is part of the S4 Summary group generic. Methods for it must use the signature x, ..., na.rm.

‘plotmath’ for the use of sum in plot annotation.

References

Becker, R. A., Chambers, J. M. and Wilks, A. R. (1988) The New S Language. Wadsworth & Brooks/Cole.

See Also

colSums for row and column sums.

Examples

## Pass a vector to sum, and it will add the elements together.
sum(1:5)

## Pass several numbers to sum, and it also adds the elements.
sum(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)

## In fact, you can pass vectors into several arguments, and everything gets added.
sum(1:2, 3:5)

## If there are missing values, the sum is unknown, i.e., also missing, ....
sum(1:5, NA)
## ... unless  we exclude missing values explicitly:
sum(1:5, NA, na.rm = TRUE)
[Package base version 3.6.1 ]

The symbols “|” and “&” are also very used in R and mean “or” and “and”, respectively. For example:

In [92]:

ScoreStudent

In [93]:

ScoreStudent

10 1J

The tilde operator (~) is used to separate the left- and right sides of a model formula. For instance:

In [94]:

Functions¶

Most of the time, we are going to use functions that were already created by others. This makes our life much easier because we don’t need to write down codes to represent complex mathematical formulas, algorithms or statistical analysis (a very smart person has already done this job for us). Functions are used in the following way: Function (argument 1, argument 2, argument 3, …) The number and type of arguments depend on the function you are using. For example:

In [95]:
sum (1,10) # returns the sum of all the values present in its arguments (i.e. 1 and 10)
11
In [96]:
sqrt (4) # it calculates the square root of a number or a series of numbers
2
In [97]:
log (4) # it calculates the natural logarithm of a number or a series of numbers
1.38629436111989
In [98]:
min (1,2,5,0.5) # returns the smaller number of all the values present in its arguments
0.5
In [99]:
max (1,2,5,0.5) # returns the larger number of all the values present in its arguments
5
In [100]:
mean (1,2,5,0.5) # returns the average of all the values present in its arguments
1
In [101]:
range (1,2,5,0.5) # returns the range of all the values present in its arguments
  1. 0.5
  2. 5
In [102]:
prod (1,2,5,0.5) # returns the product of all the values present in its arguments
5

We can also create our own functions! This can be done using the function "function'. Lets' create below a function to divide the first element (a) by the second (b) and then multiple by the third (c).

In [103]:
# First we define our function
our_first_function = function (a,b,c){
    ( a / b ) * c 
} 

# Now let's use it!
our_first_function (2,2,5)
5

Removing objects from workspace¶

To exclude objects, you can use the function “rm”, see below.

In [104]:
rm (our_first_function)

Remove all objects, except "x".

In [106]:
x <- sd (c(1 , 5, 7, 3))
rm(list=setdiff(ls(), c("x")))

To remove all object all object, use:

In [108]:
rm(list = ls())

Packages¶

To run some functions, we have to install and load some packages. Packages are units of reproducible R code, that contain functions, documentations that describe how to use these functions, and sample data. Let’s take the package “vegan” as an example. This is a very popular package for multivariate analysis in Ecology. You can install this package clicking on the tab “packages” (inferior left window) and then Install, which should open another window that allow you to search for the packages name. You can also use the function below.

In [109]:
install.packages ("vegan")

Warning message:
"package 'vegan' is in use and will not be installed"

To load the package, you can use function “require” or “library”. For instance:

In [110]:
require (vegan) # it also works if you run: library (vegan)

Don’t forget that you have to be connect with the internet to download the package. Be aware that some incompatibilities between old versions of R and the packages can occur! Try to uninstall the old version of R and install the new one with some regularity (~every three months).

Help¶

When we are not sure about how to use a specific function or when we don’t know the name of the function that do a specific task, it is a good idea to explore the help documentations that are available in R. To access the R documentation of a specific function, we just have to type question mark followed by the name of the function or use the function “help”. For example:

In [111]:
? seq #it also works if you use: help (seq)
seq {base}R Documentation

Sequence Generation

Description

Generate regular sequences. seq is a standard generic with a default method. seq.int is a primitive which can be much faster but has a few restrictions. seq_along and seq_len are very fast primitives for two common cases.

Usage

seq(...)

## Default S3 method:
seq(from = 1, to = 1, by = ((to - from)/(length.out - 1)),
    length.out = NULL, along.with = NULL, ...)

seq.int(from, to, by, length.out, along.with, ...)

seq_along(along.with)
seq_len(length.out)

Arguments

...

arguments passed to or from methods.

from, to

the starting and (maximal) end values of the sequence. Of length 1 unless just from is supplied as an unnamed argument.

by

number: increment of the sequence.

length.out

desired length of the sequence. A non-negative number, which for seq and seq.int will be rounded up if fractional.

along.with

take the length from the length of this argument.

Details

Numerical inputs should all be finite (that is, not infinite, NaN or NA).

The interpretation of the unnamed arguments of seq and seq.int is not standard, and it is recommended always to name the arguments when programming.

seq is generic, and only the default method is described here. Note that it dispatches on the class of the first argument irrespective of argument names. This can have unintended consequences if it is called with just one argument intending this to be taken as along.with: it is much better to use seq_along in that case.

seq.int is an internal generic which dispatches on methods for "seq" based on the class of the first supplied argument (before argument matching).

Typical usages are 

seq(from, to)
seq(from, to, by= )
seq(from, to, length.out= )
seq(along.with= )
seq(from)
seq(length.out= )

The first form generates the sequence from, from+/-1, ..., to (identical to from:to).

The second form generates from, from+by, ..., up to the sequence value less than or equal to to. Specifying to - from and by of opposite signs is an error. Note that the computed final value can go just beyond to to allow for rounding error, but is truncated to to. (‘Just beyond’ is by up to 1e-10 times abs(from - to).)

The third generates a sequence of length.out equally spaced values from from to to. (length.out is usually abbreviated to length or len, and seq_len is much faster.)

The fourth form generates the integer sequence 1, 2, ..., length(along.with). (along.with is usually abbreviated to along, and seq_along is much faster.)

The fifth form generates the sequence 1, 2, ..., length(from) (as if argument along.with had been specified), unless the argument is numeric of length 1 when it is interpreted as 1:from (even for seq(0) for compatibility with S). Using either seq_along or seq_len is much preferred (unless strict S compatibility is essential).

The final form generates the integer sequence 1, 2, ..., length.out unless length.out = 0, when it generates integer(0).

Very small sequences (with from - to of the order of 10^{-14} times the larger of the ends) will return from.

For seq (only), up to two of from, to and by can be supplied as complex values provided length.out or along.with is specified. More generally, the default method of seq will handle classed objects with methods for the Math, Ops and Summary group generics.

seq.int, seq_along and seq_len are primitive.

Value

seq.int and the default method of seq for numeric arguments return a vector of type "integer" or "double": programmers should not rely on which.

seq_along and seq_len return an integer vector, unless it is a long vector when it will be double.

References

Becker, R. A., Chambers, J. M. and Wilks, A. R. (1988) The New S Language. Wadsworth & Brooks/Cole.

See Also

The methods seq.Date and seq.POSIXt.

:, rep, sequence, row, col.

Examples

seq(0, 1, length.out = 11)
seq(stats::rnorm(20)) # effectively 'along'
seq(1, 9, by = 2)     # matches 'end'
seq(1, 9, by = pi)    # stays below 'end'
seq(1, 6, by = 3)
seq(1.575, 5.125, by = 0.05)
seq(17) # same as 1:17, or even better seq_len(17)
[Package base version 3.6.1 ]

These R documentations follow a standardize format, which is basically composed of:

  • Description: Brief description of the function
  • Usage: How to use the function and the arguments that are required.
  • Arguments: Description of each argument
  • Details: Details about the use and application of the function
  • Values: List and explain the outputs of the function
  • Notes: Some general notes about the function
  • Authors: List the authors of the function
  • References: References used to create the function
  • See also: Shows other functions that are somehow related with the function searched
  • Examples: Provides some examples showing the usage of the function.

To search for functions that do some specific tasks, you can use the function “help.search” or “??”. For example:

In [112]:
?? logarithm

starting httpd help server ... done

If you are connected with the internet, you can search the files associated with the word searched in the help files located in the R website. For instance:

In [113]:
RSiteSearch("logarithm")

A search query has been submitted to http://search.r-project.org
The results page should open in your browser shortly

The “R community” is very active, friendly and cooperative. There are many websites, blogs and mailing lists that you can search for help and information from other R users, including:

  • stackoverflow https://stackoverflow.com (my favorite)
  • R-Bloggers http://www.r-bloggers.com
  • Mailing lists https://www.r-project.org/mail.html
  • R cookbook http://www.cookbook-r.com
  • Youtube https://www.youtube.com/ (many different channels teach how to use R)

Free R manuals can also be found on the internet. On the R website, search for manuals (https://cran.r-project.org/manuals.html). More specific manuals, especially related with statistics and plots, can be found on the website https://cran.r-project.org/other-docs.html.

Data classes¶

R supports some basic data classes that are useful for us to know:

  1. Logical - two possible values (binary) represented by TRUE and FALSE.
In [114]:
logical_object <- TRUE 
class (logical_object) # Function that tell us the class of a given object
'logical'
  1. Numeric – integers (without a fractional component) and float numbers (numbers that are not integers, because it includes a fraction represented in decimal format)
In [117]:
int_num_object <- 5
class (int_num_object)
'numeric'
In [118]:
float_num_object <- 5.2
class (float_num_object)
'numeric'
  1. Character/string – composed of characters (strings), not numbers. Numbers are only used as characters/ strings if they are not going to participate in math equations. Example zip code, phone numbers.
In [119]:
str_obj <- "goat"
class (str_obj)
'character'
  1. Factor – Data composed of categories that not follow any specific order.
In [120]:
fact_obj <- factor("goat") #factor function is used to create a factor
class (fact_obj)
'factor'
  1. Ordinal – It is similar to categorical data, but ordinal data has a clear ordering among the different categories.
In [121]:
vec_ord <- c('goat','horse','turtle') #this is a vector. We are going to talk about it in the next sections
ord_obj <- factor (vec_ord, levels = c('goat','horse','turtle'), order = TRUE)
class(ord_obj)
  1. 'ordered'
  2. 'factor'

2. Creation and manipulation of data¶

Creating vectors¶

Vectors is a basic data structure in R, and consist of a series of elements. To create a vector, you can use the function “c()”. For instance:

In [172]:
num_vec <- c(2,4,6,8,10) # numeric vector
print (num_vec)

[1]  2  4  6  8 10
In [173]:
car_vec <- c("green","blue","red") # caracter vector
print (car_vec)

[1] "green" "blue"  "red"

Use the function “seq” to create sequences of numbers, such as:

In [175]:
seq_vec <- seq (0,10,2) # arg: from, to, by 
print (seq_vec)

[1]  0  2  4  6  8 10

Number repetition can be done using the function “rep”. See below.

In [176]:
char_vec <- rep ("red",5) #repeat red ten times
print (char_vec)

[1] "red" "red" "red" "red" "red"
In [177]:
col_seq <- c(rep("red",3),
             rep("blue",3)) # You can use a function within another function
print (col_seq)

[1] "red"  "red"  "red"  "blue" "blue" "blue"

You can encode a vector as a factor (containing categories) using the function “factor”. For example:

In [178]:
col_seq <- factor (col_seq) # red and blue will be consider different levels of a category
print (col_seq)

[1] red  red  red  blue blue blue
Levels: blue red
In [179]:
size_cat <- c(rep ("short", 3),
              "medium",
              rep ("tall",2))
size_cat <- factor (size_cat, 
                    order = T, 
                    levels = c("short","medium","tall")) # ordinal vector
print (size_cat)

[1] short  short  short  medium tall   tall  
Levels: short < medium < tall
In [180]:
num_cat <- factor(c(1,1,2,2,3,3,4,4))
sum (num_cat) #doesn’t make sense for a factor – error message should appear

Error in Summary.factor(structure(c(1L, 1L, 2L, 2L, 3L, 3L, 4L, 4L), .Label = c("1", : 'sum' not meaningful for factors
Traceback:

1. Summary.factor(structure(c(1L, 1L, 2L, 2L, 3L, 3L, 4L, 4L), .Label = c("1", 
 . "2", "3", "4"), class = "factor"), na.rm = FALSE)
2. stop(gettextf("%s not meaningful for factors", sQuote(.Generic)))

Logical vectors can also be easily created. See below.

In [182]:
log_vec <- as.logical(c(T,T,F,T,F,F,F))
print (log_vec)

[1]  TRUE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE
In [184]:
log_vec <- as.logical(c(1,1,0,1,0,0,0))
print (log_vec)

[1]  TRUE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE

You can create vectors using a random sampling procedure or based on specific probability distributions. For instance:

In [185]:
random_sample<- sample (0:100,size=1000, replace=T) # sample from 0 to 100 a thousand times with replacement
hist (random_sample) # plot a histogram
In [186]:
vec_normal<-rnorm (1000,mean=5,sd=2) #normal distribution, 1000 N with mean 5 and SD=2
hist(vec_normal)
In [187]:
vec_poisson<-rpois (1000, lambda=5) # poisson distribution, 1000 N with lambda=5
hist (vec_poisson)
In [188]:
vec_log<-rlnorm(1000, meanlog = 1, sdlog = 0.2) # log normal distribution
hist (vec_log)
In [189]:
vec_unif<-runif(1000,min=0,max=10)#1000 values varying from 0 to 10 – unif distribution 
hist(vec_unif)
In [190]:
vec_binary <- rbinom(20, 1, 0.5) # vector based on a random binomial generator 
hist (vec_binary)

The function summary provide a fast summary of the values in your vector.

In [191]:
summary (vec_normal)

   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

Operations with vectors¶

Mathematical operations and functions can be easily applied to numerical vectors, for instance:

In [192]:

You can also sort your vector and replace specific number or elements, for example:

In [196]:
set.seed (1) # creating simulations or random objects that can be reproduced
random_sample <- sample(0:10,size=10,replace=F)

print (random_sample)

 [1]  8  3  6  0  1  4  2 10  9  7
In [197]:
random_sample <-sort(random_sample,decreasing=T)#sorting the vector, from large to small numbers
print (random_sample)

 [1] 10  9  8  7  6  4  3  2  1  0

Let’s say that we want to replace the number 10 with the number 11

In [198]:
random_sample [1] <- 11 #replace a specific element of the vector (OPTION 1)
print (random_sample)

 [1] 11  9  8  7  6  4  3  2  1  0
In [199]:
set.seed(1)
random_sample <- sample(0:10,size=10,replace=F) # re-creating the original vector
random_sample <-ifelse(random_sample == 10,11, random_sample) # if the value is 10 replace with 11, else keep the original number. (OPTION 2)

print (sort (random_sample, decreasing=T))

 [1] 11  9  8  7  6  4  3  2  1  0

Creating tables, matrices and dataframes¶

Matrices and dataframes are a group of vectors arranged in different rows and/or columns.
The main difference between these classes is that matrices accept just a single type of vectors at a time (characters or numeric, for instance), while dataframes may be composed of different types of vectors. Let’s create a matrix and a dataframe based on multiple vectors.

Importing and exporting data with R¶

Most of the time, you will work with spreadsheets created in different programs, such as Excel. So, it is essential that you know how to import data to R. Besides that, in many situations, you have to export the result of analyses conducted in R to other programs. Below, you can find some examples about how to do it. The best way to import data into R is using a txt file or a csv file (Excel). To transform a xlsx file (defaut format of excel) into a csv file or a txt file, you have to: open the excel file > click on the “file” tab > click on save as > in the option “Save as type”, change “xlsx” to “CSV (Comma delimited) (.csv)” or “Text (Tab delimited) (.txt)”. Please transform the file “earth_worm.xlsx“ to csv and txt. Keep the same file name (“earth_worm.csv” and “earth_worm.txt”). Double check that all files were saved in the current directory (same folder where the R project was saved). Now, follow the steps below.

In [211]:
earth_worm <- read.csv ("earth_worm.csv", header=T, sep=";") # header=T means header is present, “sep” the field separator character. 
earth_worm <- read.table ("earth_worm.txt", header=T)

If your file is not in the current R directory, you can search for the file in your computer using the code below.

In [213]:
earth_worm <- read.table(file.choose(), header=TRUE)

You can also import the data using CTRL+C with the auxiliary of the function clipboard. See below.

In [ ]:
#first copy (CTRL+C) the table and then run the code below
earth_worm <- read.table(file = "clipboard", sep = "", header=TRUE)

To export a dataframe or a matrix from R to a "txt" or "csv" file, you can use:

In [214]:
write.table (earth_worm,file="earth_worm2.csv", sep=",") #csv
write.table (earth_worm,file="earth_worm2.txt", sep=",") #txt

The dataframe looks OK, but what we want is to create a site-species matrix to explore changes in species abundance among the sites. How can we do that? The function “dcast” of the package “reshape2” is very useful to do these kind of tasks, saving us a lot of time. See below.

grassland_forest_pivoted <- dcast (grassland_forest, Habitat~Species, length)
# first argument is the data, the second is a formula (in this case, habitat will be the rows and species the columns),

  2. 'y'

To change the color of the points, we use the argument “col”. A list with the code for several different colors can be found in this link: http://www.stat.columbia.edu/~tzheng/files/Rcolor.pdf

The argument pch change the symbol of the object. The defaut symbol is an empty circle (code =1), but we can choose among several different types. The codification for each one of them can be seen below.

Source: https://www.statmethods.net/advgraphs/parameters.html

For this example, we are going to use the square symbol (code=0).

Boxplots¶

Boxplots are graphs that are used to explore the values of a continuous variable among different levels of a categorical variable. Central horizontal lines within the boxes are the median values; upper and lower hinges are the third and first quartiles, respectively; and whiskers indicate the maximum and minimum values. To explore this kind of graph, let’s load the file “ciano” into R.

In [339]:
ciano <- read.table ("ciano.txt",header=T)
summary (ciano)

     toxin       block       temp    nutri  
 Min.   : 60.0   A:18   control:36   N :24  
 1st Qu.: 86.0   B:18   High   :36   NP:24  
 Median : 96.5   C:18                P :24  
 Mean   :100.6   D:18                       
 3rd Qu.:114.5                              
 Max.   :136.0

This data was taken from an experimental study that explored the addition effect of nutrients on the toxin production of cyanobacteria. The column "nutri" is categorical and contains three treatment levels: N addition, P addition, and N+P addition. The column “toxin” is composed of different values of toxin found in the water. Therefore, this variable is continuous and will be consider as our response. Let’s use the function plot to create the boxplot.

In [343]:
par (mai=c(1,1,0,0.2))
plot (toxin~nutri, data=ciano)

The different levels of the category are placed in the plot according to their alphabetic order. To change the order, we can use the function “factor” and its argument “levels”. See below.

In [345]:
par (mai=c(1,1,0,0.2))
ciano$nutri<-factor(ciano$nutri, levels =c("N","P","NP"))
plot (toxin~nutri, data=ciano,
     col=c("red","green","blue")) #define color for each box

Barplots¶

Similar to boxplots, barplots are also used to show the variation of values of a continuous variable among the different levels of a categorical variable. Bars usually represent mean values and, in most cases, error bars (CI, SD, etc) are present in each bar to show the variation around the mean. First, we will create a dataset.

In [346]:
sp1 <- c(12,15,13,14)
sp2 <-c(18,17,14,19)
sp3 <-c(10,11,13,8)
abund <-cbind(sp1,sp2,sp3)

Second, we will use the function barplot to plot the data.

In [357]:
par (mai=c(1,1,0,0.2))
barplot (abund, beside=T) # add legend using the legend

This plot shows us the raw numbers for each element of the vector. To show the mean and SD for each column, we will have to conduct some extra steps. First, we will create our own function that will return two things: the mean and the sd.

In [358]:
mean_sd <- function(x) {
    c(Mean = mean(x), SD = sd (x))
}

The function that we just created has a single argument: “x”. This “x” is used to compute the mean and the SD. Easy, isn’t it? Now, let’s run our function and then plot the data.

In [363]:
abund<-as.data.frame(abund) #transforming matrix into a dataframe, otherwise the sapply function return some weird output. 

summary_data <-sapply (abund, mean_sd) # this function allows you to run a function in each column of your dataframe.

plotTop <- round(max(summary_data[1,]+ summary_data[2,]), digit=-1) 
#First we find the upper limit in our data (based on SE) and then we round the number (aesthetic detail)

names <- c("sp1","sp2","sp3")

par (mai=c(1,1,0.2,0.2))
barCenters <- barplot(summary_data[1,], names.arg=names, col="gray", las=1, ylim=c(0, plotTop),
                     ylab = "Abundance", xlab= "Species", cex.lab = 1.4, cex.axis = 1.2)

arrows(barCenters, summary_data[1,]- summary_data[2,], # coordinates of points from which to draw (x and y).
       barCenters, summary_data[1,]+ summary_data[2,], # coordinates of points to which to draw (x1 and y1).
       lwd=1, angle=90, code=3) # lwd= type of line, code= determining kind of arrows to be drawn

That looks good. You can export the figure if you want using the "tiff" function.

Plots to explore multicollinearity in the database¶

Multicollinearity, or simplify the high intercorrelations or inter-associations among the independent variables, is a major concern in many statistical tests. R has some nice ways to explore how variables are inter-correlated. Here, we are going to see the function “pairs”. First, let’s load the dataset “ozone” into R.

In [375]:
ozone <-read.table("ozone.txt",header=T) 
head (ozone,3)
radtempwindozone
190 67 7.441
118 72 8.036
149 74 12.612
In [386]:
par (mai=c(0.1,0.1,0,0))
pairs (ozone,cex=0.6)

Imagine that this data come from three different localities (37 observations in each one) and we are interested to see if these correlations are still consistent within each locality. To that, we create unique colors for each locality and plot the figure again.

In [385]:
par (mai=c(0.1,0.1,0,0))
pairs(ozone, cex =0.6,
      col= rep(c(1,2,3),
               each=37))

We can also add a trendline in each plot. For instance:

In [387]:
par (mai=c(0.1,0.1,0,0))
pairs(ozone, panel=panel.smooth,
     cex=0.6)

If all the variables are continuous, you can also use the function "chart.Correlation" from the package PerformanceAnalytics. This package provides the correlation coefficients among variables as well as the histogram of each variable.

In [394]:
require("PerformanceAnalytics")

par (mai=c(0,0,0,0))

Another alternative is the function corrplot from the package corrplot

4. Statistics¶

Linear regression¶

Linear model containing a continuous dependent variable (response) and one continuous independent variable (explanatory). Main assumptions:

  1. residuals are normally distributed
  2. homogeneity of variance
  3. Independence of sampling units

To explore linear regression, we are going to use the dataset "earth worm".

In [426]:
earth_worm <- read.csv ("earth_worm.csv", header=T,sep=";")

The function to run linear regressions is “lm”. Here, we will explore how the soil pH affects the density of earth worms.

In [427]:
regression <- lm (density ~ pH.soil, data=earth_worm)

To verify visually if the assumptions of the model were not violated (specially the i and ii), we can use the function “plot”.

In [433]:
par(mfrow=c(2,2),mai=c(0.9,0.9,0.3,0.3))
plot (regression)

There is a clear outlier in the dataset (#8)! In a serius study, the outlier should be investigated in more details. For the sake of time, here we are going to remove it from the analysis.

In [434]:
earth_worm <- earth_worm [-8,] #remove outlier
regression <- lm (density ~ pH.soil, data=earth_worm) #run analysis again

par(mfrow=c(2,2),mai=c(0.9,0.9,0.3,0.3))
plot (regression) # check assumptions

Much better now! Assuming that all the assumptions were not violated, we can now explore the results using the function “summary”.

In [435]:

Multiple regression¶

Multiple regressions are essentially linear regressions with more than 1 explanatory variable (independent variables). Main assumptions:

  1. residuals are normally distributed
  2. homogeneity of variance
  3. Independence of sampling units
  4. No or little multicollinearity To explore this type of analysis, we are going to test the effect of the soil PH and the concentration of water in the soil on the density of earth worms. Thus, instead of conducting two linear regressions, we can test the effect of these two variables in a single analysis. To conduct a multiple regression, follow the code below.
In [443]:
earth_worm <- read.csv ("earth_worm.csv", header=T,sep=";")
earth_worm <- earth_worm [-8,] # remove outlier 

mult_regress <- lm (density ~ pH.soil+soaked, data=earth_worm) 
#the plus sign indicates the function that we have one more explanatory variable

Before checking the results of the analysis, we should take a look on some diagnostic plots to see if the assumptions of the model were not violated.

In [445]:
par(mfrow=c(2,2),mai=c(0.9,0.9,0.3,0.3))

T-test and paired T-test¶

T-test is used to determine if there is a significant difference between the mean of two groups. Thus, to run this analysis, you need a continuous response variable and a categorical explanatory variable with two levels. Main assumptions:

  1. residuals are normally distributed
  2. homogeneity of variance
  3. Independence of sampling units

To explore this analysis, please load the ciano_red database.

Analysis of Variance (ANOVA)¶

Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) is an analysis composed of one continuous response variable and categorical explanatory variables. People usually make the number of categorical variables explicit in the name of the analysis, for instance: One-way ANOVA (1 categorical variable), Two-way ANOVA (2 categorical variables), and so on. Main assumptions:

  1. Residuals are normally distributed
  2. Homogeneity of variance
  3. Independence of sampling units
  4. No or little multicollinearity

We will use an One-way ANOVA to explore how the density of earth worm vary among soils with different levels of water concentration (variable: soaked). The function that we will use is called "aov".

In [474]:
earth_worm <- read.csv ("earth_worm.csv", header=T, sep=";")
earth_worm <- earth_worm [-8,] #remove outlier in line 8. See the linear regression section for 
# more details or just try to run the analysis without removing line 8.
anova_worms <- aov (density~soaked, data=earth_worm)

To access diagnostic plots, you can again use the function “plot”.

Generalized Linear Models (GLM)¶

GLMs are a flexible generalization of linear (multiple) regressions that allow the user to use response variables with different probability distributions (i.e., not just restricted to normal distribution). GLMs are composed of three main components:

Systematic component: The explanatory components (independent variables).
Random component: the probability distribution of the response variable (binomial, gaussian, Gamma, inverse gaussian, poisson, quasi, quasibinomial, quasipoisson).
Link function: link between random and systematic components. There is a default link function for each probability distribution, but this can be changed by the user (you have to know what you are doing). See the default options below:

Probability distribution Link function
Binomial Logit
Gaussian Identity
Gamma Inverse
Inverse gaussian 1/mu^2
Poisson Log
Quasi Identity
Quasibinomial Logit
Quasipoisson Log

Main assumptions:

  1. Independence of sampling units
  2. The residuals don’t need to be normal distributed, but should follow the distribution of the exponential family specified in the model (bionomial, poisson, etc).
  3. Homogeneity of variance (some authors may disagree about this one)

Here, we will run three glm models with response variables with different probability distributions: poisson (count data – discrete numbers/integers), binomial (presence-absence, proportion data) and gaussian (continuous data). Let’s start with the normal distribution (gaussian). Load the “earth_worm” dataset.

A good way to check for overdispersion in count models is by looking at hanging rootogram, which compare the empirical frequencies (observed data) with fitted frequencies. Gray bars over the 0 line indicate overfitting, and bars under the 0 line suggest underfitting. At the zero line, the model fits the data perfectly. Consider using Negative Binomial generalized linear model, hurdle and zero-inflated regressions rather than Poisson GLM when overdispersion/underdispersion is high.

Generalized Least Squares (GLS)¶

A Generalized Least Square (GLS) is a method of parameter estimation which accounts for the structure in the error term. In this sense, it can be used to model heterosdasticity in the data and also the lack of independence caused by evolutionary history (phylogenetic component). In this section, we are going to see how we can deal with these two peculiarities of ecological data. Please, load the “Squid” dataset in R. The goal here is to explore how testicle weight of squids vary with body size (dorsal mantle length - DML).

Mixed model¶

Mixed models are used to analyze nested data (sometimes also called hierarchical data or multilevel data). For instance, many observations of the same subject are not independent. This hamper us to use regular linear models (such as ANOVA, linear regression, etc) due to the assumption of independence of sampling units (iii). In the past, many researches use to calculate means for each individual and then analyze the data with regular linear models. However, this approach reduces sample size and also hide intrinsic variation at the individual level. Mixed models were created to overcome this issue with its extra random term. In other words, the mixed model allows us to model individual variance (or other non-independent observations) by assuming different intercepts or even slopes for each individual. Main assumptions

  1. The errors have constant variance (Homogeneity of variance)
  2. The errors are independent
  3. The errors are normally distributed

To explore mixed models in R, we are going to use the dataset RIKZ, which was download from the package AED. Take a look on the figure below to understand the data structure:

Source: Zuur et al. (2009) Mixed Effects Models and Extensions in Ecology with R This dataset is composed of richness measurements (macrofauna) taken on 9 beaches, and on each beach 5 sites were sampled. As you can imagine, all the sites sampled in each beach are not independent of each other, they are pseudo-replicates.

Let’s start loading the data to R.

NAP stands for NAP the height of a sampling station compared to mean tidal level. Exposure is an index composed of wave action, length of the surf zone, slope, grain size, and the depth of the anaerobic layer. Here, we are interested about how NAP and exposure affect the richness of the macrofauna. Richness is count data, so the best approach would be using a generalized linear mixed model (GLMM) with poisson distribution. We will do this in a minute, but, for the sake of simplicity, let’s use linear mixed model for now. To run a random intercept linear mixed model, we can use the function “lmer” of the package “lme4”.

Finally, we should explore how good our model is when faced with "new data". This is a fundamental step to test the predictive power of our model. Most studies conduct only in-sample evaluation of their models (evaluation using train data) and forget to include an out-of-sample evaluation (evaluation using test data) in their statistical analysis. The steps of a cross-validation are:

  1. Randomly split the data set into k-subsets (or k-fold) (for example 5 subsets)
  2. Reserve one subset and train the model on all other subsets
  3. Test the model on the reserved subset and record the prediction error
  4. Repeat this process until each of the k subsets has served as the test set.
  5. Compute the average of the k recorded errors. This is called the cross-validation error serving as the performance metric for the model.

source: STHDA

First, we are going to calculate the in-sample R2 and then we are going to calculate out-of-sample R2 using the cross-validation method. Compare the two values.

                  data=train_data,

Rarefaction¶

Richness of species usually increase with the number of samples and number of individuals collected. In order to control for this bias, the rarefaction technique is usually used rather than the absolute richness. Rarefaction consists of randomly re-sampling the pool of N samples several times and then computing the average number of species. This process allows us to generate expected richness for sub-samples of the dataset and even understand how richness increase as we increase the sample size (usually referred as rarefaction curves). Main assumption:

  1. The sample is a statistically adequate, representative sample of the community
  2. Conspecifics are uniform randomly dispersed
  3. Species are dispersed independently

For this section, we are going to use the database available on the package “vegan”, called “BCI”.

In [587]:
require (vegan)
data(BCI) # sites vs species 
?BCI # Description of the database

Barro Colorado Island Tree Counts

Description

Tree counts in 1-hectare plots in the Barro Colorado Island and associated site information.

Usage

data(BCI.env)

Format

A data frame with 50 plots (rows) of 1 hectare with counts of trees on each plot with total of 225 species (columns). Full Latin names are used for tree species. The names were updated against http://www.theplantlist.org and Kress et al. (2009) which allows matching 207 of species against doi: 10.5061/dryad.63q27 (Zanne et al., 2014). The original species names are available as attribute original.names of BCI. See Examples for changed names.

For BCI.env, a data frame with 50 plots (rows) and nine site variables derived from Pyke et al. (2001) and Harms et al. (2001):

UTM.EW:

UTM coordinates (zone 17N) East-West.

UTM.NS:

UTM coordinates (zone 17N) North-South.

Precipitation:

Precipitation in mm per year.

Elevation:

Elevation in m above sea level.

Age.cat:

Forest age category.

Geology:

The Underlying geological formation.

Habitat:

Dominant habitat type based on the map of habitat types in 25 grid cells in each plot (Harms et al. 2001, excluding streamside habitat). The habitat types are Young forests (ca. 100 years), old forests on > 7 degree slopes (OldSlope), old forests under 152 m elevation (OldLow) and at higher elevation (OldHigh) and Swamp forests.

River:

"Yes" if there is streamside habitat in the plot.

EnvHet:

Environmental Heterogeneity assessed as the Simpson diversity of frequencies of Habitat types in 25 grid cells in the plot.

Details

Data give the numbers of trees at least 10 cm in diameter at breast height (1.3 m above the ground) in each one hectare square of forest. Within each one hectare square, all individuals of all species were tallied and are recorded in this table.

The data frame contains only the Barro Colorado Island subset of the original data.

The quadrats are located in a regular grid. See BCI.env for the coordinates.

A full description of the site information in BCI.env is given in Pyke et al. (2001) and Harms et al. (2001). N.B. Pyke et al. (2001) and Harms et al. (2001) give conflicting information about forest age categories and elevation.

Source

https://science.sciencemag.org/content/suppl/2002/01/24/295.5555.666.DC1 for community data and References for environmental data.

MANOVA is simply an ANOVA with multiple response variables. In this section, we are going to learn a MANOVA that is based on permutation tests (PERMANOVA) and do not require the assumption of multivariate normality.

Clusters¶

As the name suggest, clusters are used to organize groups according to their similarity. You need to be aware that there are many different indexes to estimate similarities and many algorithms to create clusters. In R, we can create hierarchical clusters using the function “hclust”, but before that we need to create resemble matrices:

In [613]:
require (vegan)
data (dune)
dune.dist<-vegdist(dune,method="bray")  # resemble matrix based on bray-curtis dissimilarity

Now, let’s create two hierarchical clusters using two different algorithms: ward and average.

In [615]:
par(mfrow=c(1,2))

clus_ward<-hclust(dune.dist,method="ward.D")
plot(clus_ward,cex=0.6)

clus_avg<-hclust(dune.dist,method="average")
plot(clus_avg,,cex=0.6)

Unconstrained ordinations¶

Unconstrained ordinations are a way to reduce multiple variables into a few number of orthogonal axes that explain most part of the variation in the dataset. In order to work, the variables in the dataset must be correlated with each other, which is usually the case. Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is probably the most simple and common method of ordination. The main difference between PCA from the other ordination methods is that the PCA use exclusively the Euclidian metric to estimate the difference between sampling units. To run a PCA, we can use the function “rda” of the package vegan.

In [616]:
require (vegan)
data(varechem) #vegan data, soil samples: physical-chemical composition

res_pca<-rda(varechem,scale=T) 
# Scale=T is used to standardize (have the same 
#unit of variance, mean=0 SD=1) the variables prior the analysis.

Let’s take a look at the results. The function summary provides many pieces of information regarding the analysis, including the importance of the components, variable coordinates (called species scores) and site coordinates (called site scores).

Constrained ordinations¶

The next step is constrain the ordinations by other variables. In order words, we want to verify how much of our multivariate response variable can be explained by our explanatory variables. Here, we are going to explore three main methods to do it: i) redundancy analysis (RDA), which is a constrained version of a PCA; ii) db-RDA, which is a constrained version of a PCoA; and iii) canonical correspondence analysis (CCA), which is a constrained version of a Correspondence Analysis (CA). All these analyses can be used to explore how biological communities respond to environmental variables and that’s what we are going to do here in these examples. Here, we are going to use the "varespec" and "varechem" datasets.

In [642]:
require (vegan)

data(varespec); data (varechem) #; allows you to run multiple pieces of codes in a single row
# Plant composition and environmental variables of lichen pastures

To run a RDA with community data, we first need to transform our data using Hellinger transformation to avoid biases caused by some particularities of the Euclidean distance metric.

In [643]:
varespec_trans <-decostand(varespec,method="hellinger")

Now, we are free to run the analysis! For this example, let’s use the first three explanatory variables.

In [644]:
N<-varechem[,1]
P<-varechem[,2]
K<-varechem[,3]

res_rda<-rda (varespec_trans~N+P+K)
summary(res_rda) #shows you the amount of the inertia explained by the analysis, 
#the amount of explanation of each axis, and the scores.
